			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Role-Based Approach towards Modular Language Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/ChristianWende.html">Christian Wende</a>, <a href="../profile/NilsThieme.html">Nils Thieme</a>, <a href="../profile/SteffenZschaler.html">Steffen Zschaler</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_19">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_19</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s central contribution is a modularization mechanism (roles) for structuring language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> Role-based modularity enables reuse of language components across variants and contexts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Such modular language engineering is typically realized and evaluated through supporting tooling.
</li></ul></li></ul>
